<sharepoint_security_guide>
<title>SHAREPOINT SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>SharePoint security testing covers Microsoft-specific CVEs, deserialization attacks, API discovery, permission misconfiguration, and document library exposure. Critical for enterprise environments with sensitive documents and workflows.</critical>

<scope>
- SharePoint version detection and CVE testing
- Deserialization vulnerabilities
- REST API and SOAP endpoint discovery
- Permission and access control bypass
- Document library exposure
- Search query injection
- User profile enumeration
- Custom web parts exploitation
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Detect SharePoint version and check for known CVEs.
2. Enumerate API endpoints (REST, SOAP, OData).
3. Test for deserialization vulnerabilities.
4. Assess permission configurations and access controls.
5. Test document library security.
6. Enumerate users and test search functionality.
</methodology>

<version_detection>
{% raw %}
# SharePoint version:
curl -I https://sharepoint.example.com/_layouts/15/
# SPRequestGuid header
curl https://sharepoint.example.com/_vti_inf.html
# Contains version info

# Common CVEs:
# CVE-2019-0604: RCE via deserialization
# CVE-2020-0646: RCE
# CVE-2020-1147: XML parser vulnerability
{% endraw %}
</version_detection>

<deserialization_attacks>
{% raw %}
# CVE-2019-0604 exploitation:
POST /_layouts/15/picker.aspx
__VIEWSTATE: [base64_deserialization_payload]

# TypeConfuseDelegate gadget chain for RCE
{% endraw %}
</deserialization_attacks>

<api_testing>
{% raw %}
# REST API:
GET https://sharepoint.example.com/_api/web
GET https://sharepoint.example.com/_api/web/lists
GET https://sharepoint.example.com/_api/web/currentuser

# SOAP endpoints:
POST https://sharepoint.example.com/_vti_bin/lists.asmx
<soap:Envelope><soap:Body><GetListItems></GetListItems></soap:Body></soap:Envelope>

# OData:
GET https://sharepoint.example.com/_api/web/lists?$select=Title
{% endraw %}
</api_testing>

<permission_testing>
{% raw %}
# Access control bypass:
GET /_layouts/15/viewlsts.aspx  # List all libraries
GET /Shared%20Documents/sensitive.docx  # Direct file access

# Enumerate libraries:
GET /_api/web/lists?$filter=BaseTemplate eq 101

# Test anonymous access:
curl https://sharepoint.example.com/Sites/Team/Documents/
{% endraw %}
</permission_testing>

<common_payloads>
{% raw %}
# Deserialization:
__VIEWSTATE: [serialized_payload]

# Search injection:
' OR 1=1--
ContentType:Document AND Title:password

# API unauthorized access:
/_api/web/lists('guid')/items
/_api/web/siteusers

# Path traversal:
../../../sensitive-site/Documents/secret.docx
{% endraw %}
</common_payloads>

<validation>
1. Demonstrate SharePoint version and applicable CVE.
2. Show deserialization RCE (if vulnerable).
3. Prove unauthorized API access to sensitive data.
4. Document permission misconfiguration allowing access.
5. Show document library enumeration and file access.
</validation>

<impact>
- Remote Code Execution via deserialization
- Unauthorized access to sensitive documents
- Data exfiltration via API endpoints
- User enumeration and reconnaissance
- Privilege escalation through permission bypass
</impact>

<false_positives>
- _api/web endpoint accessible but returns only public site metadata
- User enumeration possible but limited to display names (no sensitive data)
- Document library visible but requires authentication for file access
- REST API responds but enforces proper permission checks on content
- _vti_bin endpoints exist but require valid authentication
- Search returns results but respects security trimming (proper filtering)
- VIEWSTATE present but properly encrypted and validated
- Anonymous access enabled but only to designated public content
</false_positives>

<pro_tips>
1. Check for CVE-2019-0604 first—it's the most impactful SharePoint RCE via deserialization.
2. _api/web/lists reveals all document library names—enumerate then test access.
3. Search queries can reveal file paths and metadata even without direct access.
4. User profile API (_api/sp.userprofiles.peoplemanager) often exposes organization structure.
5. Check for exposed OneDrive personal sites at /personal/username_domain_com/.
6. VIEWSTATE deserialization requires valid MAC key—focus on version-specific CVEs.
7. Test direct file URLs with various authentication states—permission inheritance is complex.
8. SharePoint Online vs On-Premises have different attack surfaces—verify deployment type.
9. Look for custom web parts—they often have weaker security than core SharePoint.
10. Check for exposed admin pages at _layouts/15/ that may bypass normal authentication.
</pro_tips>

<remember>SharePoint security: Check for deserialization CVEs (CVE-2019-0604, CVE-2020-0646). Test REST API (_api/web) and SOAP endpoints for unauthorized access. Enumerate document libraries and test permissions. Search functionality may allow injection. User profile data often exposed via APIs.</remember>
</sharepoint_security_guide>
